---
/**
 * Keep inline tags on one line with outer spaces (Astro whitespace).
 * Never break before <em>/<strong>/<a> after a word.
 */
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Sartre: Existence Precedes Essence – Radical Freedom and the Creation of the Self | Foundations | Identity Engineering">
	<main class="min-h-screen">
		<section class="border-b border-white/10 px-6 pt-28 pb-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<a href="/foundations" class="mb-6 inline-block text-sm text-white/40 transition hover:text-white/70">
					← Foundations
				</a>
				<div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Foundations · Sartre</div>
				<h1 class="mt-3 text-5xl font-bold tracking-tighter leading-[0.95] text-white md:text-6xl">
					Existence Precedes Essence – Radical Freedom and the Creation of the Self
				</h1>
				<p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-xl font-light leading-relaxed text-white/50">
					Sartre rejects a fixed human essence and foregrounds situated freedom: we become what we do under conditions we did not choose, while remaining responsible for how we take them up.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-12 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div class="rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] p-5 text-base leading-relaxed text-white/60">
					<strong class="text-white/80">Reading protocol on this page:</strong> First Sartre in his own terms (freedom, facticity, bad faith). Then a narrow Identity Engineering interpretation that preserves those constraints.
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">1 · Existence Precedes Essence</div>
					<p>
						Sartre’s key claim is that <strong class="text-white/80">existence precedes essence</strong>: there is no predefined human nature that determines who one must be before action.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						In <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Existentialism Is a Humanism</em> and <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Being and Nothingness</em>, this becomes a thesis about responsibility under finitude: freedom is real, but always exercised within factical situations.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">2 · Bad Faith and Authentic Existence</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-black/20 p-4 text-sm text-white/60">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Core concepts (Sartre):</strong> Bad faith (mauvaise foi) is a practical self-misrecognition in which one treats oneself as fixed object or pure freedom, avoiding the tension between facticity and transcendence.
					</div>
					<p>
						The well-known waiter example shows over-identification with role performance. Sartre’s point is not that roles are false, but that a person cannot be exhausted by any one role-description.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						So-called authenticity, in Sartre’s frame, requires owning one’s projects without denying either constraint or responsibility.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">3 · Relevance for Identity Engineering</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-400/20 bg-cyan-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Inspiration from Sartre:</strong> identity is enacted over time through commitments, revisions, and responsibility-taking.
					</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-violet-400/20 bg-violet-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">IE additions:</strong> deliberate identity design must account for both agency and situation; bad-faith dynamics indicate where declared intent and enacted pattern diverge.
					</div>
					<ul class="space-y-4">
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Existence precedes essence as process claim:</strong> no identity architecture can rely on a fixed core as finished substance; it must model ongoing project-formation.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Bad faith as mismatch signal:</strong> recurring discrepancy between chosen commitments and lived enactment can be treated as a diagnostic for identity drift.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Responsibility as practice constraint:</strong> strategic redesign without accountability to consequences collapses into rhetoric; Sartre’s pressure point is responsibility for enacted outcomes.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Freedom under conditions:</strong> options are never unlimited; the usable design task is to enlarge viable futures within factical limits rather than assume unconstrained agency.
						</li>
					</ul>
					<p class="mt-6">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Differentiation:</strong> compared with Hume, Sartre emphasizes projective responsibility; compared with Jung, he foregrounds conscious commitment rather than symbolic integration work.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Interpretive boundary:</strong> this page does not claim Sartre offers an engineering method. It extracts constraints for agency-focused identity practice.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.015] px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Sources</div>
					<ul class="space-y-2 text-base text-white/50">
						<li>
							Primary works: Jean-Paul Sartre, <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Being-and-Nothingness" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50"><em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Being and Nothingness</em></a> (1943) and <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Existentialism-Is-a-Humanism" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50"><em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Existentialism Is a Humanism</em></a> (1946).
						</li>
						<li>
							Overview: <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/spr2026/entries/sartre/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy (Spring 2026 Archive): Jean-Paul Sartre</a>.
						</li>
						<li>
							Secondary context: <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Jean-Paul-Sartre" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Encyclopaedia Britannica: Jean-Paul Sartre</a>.
						</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Related</div>
					<p>
						Sartre functions here as the existential pressure test: any identity framework that downplays responsibility, situation, or practical choice loses explanatory power.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-14">
			<div class="mx-auto flex max-w-3xl flex-col gap-4 text-sm sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between">
				<a href="/foundations" class="text-white/50 transition hover:text-white/80">← All foundations</a>
				<div class="flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-2">
					<a href="/ontology" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Ontology</a>
					<a href="/blog" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Blog</a>
					<a href="/framework" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Framework</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>
	</main>
</Layout>
